  "prompt": "What records are unlikely to be broken, ever?",
  "response": "There are several sports and historical records that many experts and enthusiasts believe are unlikely to be broken, often due to changing circumstances, rules, or technologies. Here are a few examples:\n\n### Sports Records:\n1. **Cy Young's Career Wins (Baseball)** - Cy Young won 511 games during his career. Modern pitchers start fewer games and don't pitch as many complete games as they did in the past, making this record highly improbable to be broken.\n\n2. **Cal Ripken Jr.'s Consecutive Games Played (Baseball)** - Ripken played 2,632 consecutive games, a streak that spanned over 16 years. Given the focus on rest and recovery in modern sports, few players will attempt or be allowed to play every game.\n\n3. **Wilt Chamberlain's 100-Point Game (Basketball)** - Wilt Chamberlain scored 100 points in a single NBA game in 1962. With team dynamics and defenses evolving, it's unlikely anyone will surpass this feat.\n\n### Athletic and Endurance Records:\n1. **Jahandar Shah\u2019s Reign (Shortest Monarchical Reign)** - Jahandar Shah ruled the Mughal Empire for just three months, and administrative structures today prevent such short tenures from occurring frequently.\n\n2. **Transatlantic Cable Time** - The first transatlantic telegraph cable took 17 hours to send a message from Europe to North America. Modern technology allows instant communication, making this record obsolete.\n\n### Other Records:\n1. **Usain Bolt's 100m and 200m Sprint Times** - While it's conceivable these times might be broken, Bolt's performances (9.58 seconds for the 100m and 19.19 seconds for the 200m) set an extremely high bar.\n\n2. **The Great Emu War (Australia)** - This represents a peculiar historical \"record\" where the emus effectively \"won\" against the Australian military during an attempted eradication project. Such unique and odd events are unlikely to be repeated in modern times.\n\nMany records are a product of their time and condition, making them special historical markers unlikely to be challenged due to evolving context or technological advancements.",
